      <p class="last-updated">About This Site</p>
      <h1 style="font-size: 2.4rem; margin: 8px 0 32px;">Methodology</h1>

      <h2>What this site is</h2>
      <p>An independent analytical resource on the 2026 Providence mayoral race, focused on the Democratic primary between incumbent Mayor Brett Smiley and State Representative David Morales. The goal is to give Providence voters a clear, evidence-grounded picture of where the candidates stand on real issues — and how their stated positions compare to their record and the available evidence.</p>
      <p>This is not a neutral aggregator. It is an analytical tool. Arguments for and against each candidate's positions are presented on the merits, sourced to primary documents wherever possible. Where the evidence clearly favors one position, that will be apparent. This site does not flatten genuine asymmetries to appear neutral.</p>

      <h2>Scope</h2>
      <p>This site covers Brett Smiley and David Morales — the two candidates with meaningful support, campaign infrastructure, and a realistic path to winning the September 9 Democratic primary. Michael English and independent Allen Waters are acknowledged but not covered in depth; as of April 2026, English received 1% support in the most recent poll and Waters had approximately $100 in his campaign account. The Democratic primary winner is effectively the next mayor in this strongly Democratic city. The general election is November 3, 2026.</p>

      <h2>How issues are selected</h2>
      <p>Issues are chosen based on their direct relevance to Providence residents' lives and the degree to which the candidates have meaningfully differentiated positions. Each issue is analyzed through established policy frames used by researchers and practitioners — not invented categories, but the analytical vocabulary the field actually uses. Applying these frames symmetrically to both candidates is the primary bias-reduction mechanism.</p>

      <h2>How positions are sourced</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Primary: candidate statements, press releases, campaign platforms, official votes and legislative records</li>
        <li>Secondary: local journalism (RI Current, Providence Journal, Boston Globe RI desk, ecoRI, WPRI, WJAR)</li>
        <li>Each factual claim is linked to a source. Unsourced claims are not included.</li>
        <li>Where a candidate has not stated a position, this is noted explicitly — not inferred.</li>
        <li>Internal polls are labeled as such and treated with appropriate skepticism.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How arguments are constructed</h2>
      <p>Arguments for and against each position are drawn from the best available evidence — academic research, peer cities' experience, economic data, and credible expert opinion. The goal is to steelman both sides, not to manufacture false balance. "Neither addressed" is a legitimate finding and is noted as such.</p>

      <h2>Updates</h2>
      <p>Each issue page shows its last-updated date. The site is updated as new information becomes available — new candidate statements, votes, forum appearances, or relevant data. The full revision history is publicly available on <a href="https://github.com/lfreaney/pvd-mayor" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--pvd-red);text-decoration:underline;">GitHub</a>.</p>

      <h2>Corrections</h2>
      <p>Candidates and campaigns are welcome to submit factual corrections or responses via email. All factual corrections will be noted publicly with a date. Campaign-submitted position statements will be clearly labeled as such. This site does not accept payment from campaigns or political organizations.</p>

      <h2>Who runs this</h2>
      <p>This site is maintained by <strong>Liam Freaney</strong>, a Providence-based data analytics professional and writer. Liam has a background in mathematics (Courant Institute / NYU) and has worked in analytics leadership at Sony Music, the New York Yankees, Hearst, and other organizations. He has lived in Providence since 2021 and writes op-eds on Providence civic issues for the Boston Globe, ecoRI, and other outlets.</p>
      <p>This site is not affiliated with any campaign, political party, PAC, or government entity. No candidate or campaign has paid for or reviewed content prior to publication.</p>

